Certainly! Below is an example of a single HTML file that generates a random flag for a made-up country called "Zeloria". The flag will be drawn using an HTML5 canvas, and the name of the country will be displayed above the flag.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Random Country Flag</title>
    <style>
        body {
            display: flex;
            flex-direction: column;
            align-items: center;
            justify-content: center;
            height: 100vh;
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            background-color: #f0f0f0;
        }
        canvas {
            border: 2px solid #333;
            margin-top: 20px;
        }
        h1 {
            color: #333;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<h1>Flag of Zeloria</h1>
<canvas id="flagCanvas" width="300" height="200"></canvas>

<script>
    const canvas = document.getElementById('flagCanvas');
    const ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');

    // Generate random colors
    function getRandomColor() {
        const letters = '0123456789ABCDEF';
        let color = '#';
        for (let i = 0; i < 6; i++) {
            color += letters[Math.floor(Math.random() * 16)];
        }
        return color;
    }

    // Draw the flag of Zeloria
    function drawFlag() {
        // Clear the canvas
        ctx.clearRect(0, 0, canvas.width, canvas.height);

        // Randomize number of stripes
        const stripeCount = Math.floor(Math.random() * 3) + 2; // Between 2 to 4 stripes
        const stripeHeight = canvas.height / stripeCount;

        // Draw stripes
        for (let i = 0; i < stripeCount; i++) {
            ctx.fillStyle = getRandomColor(); // Random color for each stripe
            ctx.fillRect(0, i * stripeHeight, canvas.width, stripeHeight);
        }

        // Draw a random symbol in the center (a circle)
        ctx.fillStyle = getRandomColor();
        ctx.beginPath(); 
        ctx.arc(canvas.width / 2, canvas.height / 2, 30, 0, Math.PI * 2); 
        ctx.fill();
    }

    // Execute the drawFlag function to render the flag on load
    drawFlag();
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

### How to Use:
1. Copy the entire code block above.
2. Paste it into a new `.html` file, for instance `random_flag.html`.
3. Open that file in a web browser.

This code will create a simple web application that displays a random flag for the fictional country "Zeloria" each time the page is refreshed. The flag consists of random colored stripes and a random circle symbol in the center, showcasing the use of HTML5 canvas and JavaScript.
